  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he charged him to tell no man",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] These injunctions to reticence marked especially the early part of the ministry. See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 4:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 5:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 8:56",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The reasons were probably (i) personal to the healed sufferer, lest his inward thankfulness should be dissipated by the idle and boastful gossip of curiosity (St Chrys.), but far more (ii) because, as St Matthew expressly tells us, He did not wish His ministry to be accompanied by excitement and tumult, in accordance with the prophecy of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 42:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 12:15-50",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Php 2:6-7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 5:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 18:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and (iii) because He came, not merely and not mainly, to be a great Physician and Wonder-worker, but to save men’s souls by His Revelation, His Example, and His Death.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "It is evident however that there was something very special in this case, for St Mark says (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 1:43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), “violently enjoining him, immediately He thrust him forth, and said to him, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "See that",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " you say no more to any one” (according to the right reading and translation). Clearly, although the multitudes were following Christ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 8:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), He was walking before them, and the miracle had been so sudden and instantaneous (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἰδοὺ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " … ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "εὐθέως",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") that they had not observed what had taken place. Probably our Lord desired to avoid the Levitical rites for uncleanness which the unspiritual ceremonialism of the Pharisees might have tried to force upon Him.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "On other occasions, when these reasons did not exist, He even enjoined the publication of an act of mercy, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 8:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "but go, and shew thyself to the priest",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] We find similar instances of transition from indirect to direct narration, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 23:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 74:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". See my ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Brief Greek Syntax",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 196. The priest alone could legally ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "pronounce",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " him clean.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "offer for thy cleansing",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The student should read for himself the intensely interesting and symbolic rites commanded by Moses for the legal pronunciation of a leper clean in Leviticus 14. They occupy fourteen chapters of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Negaîm",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", one of the treatises of the Mishnah.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "according as Moses commanded",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] A reference to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 14:4-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " will shew how heavy an expense the offering entailed.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for a testimony unto them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] i. e. that the priests may assure themselves that the miracle is real. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 9:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 6:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the words mean ‘for a witness ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "against",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " them.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
